This student will focus on evaluating the quality and reliability of the existing dust devil detection catalog generated from Perseverance MEDA pressure data. Rather than reviewing all ~4,000 detections, they will examine a representative subset spanning different seasons, times of day, and vortex strengths to learn how real dust devil signatures appear in the pressure record. Using visualization tools and the existing detection workflow, they will classify detections into confidence categories, identify common false positives, and develop recommendations for catalog filtering. Their work will provide an assessment of detection reliability and establish quality-control procedures that can be applied to the full dataset, ensuring that subsequent scientific analyses are based on robust vortex detections.

Vortex Catalog Quality Control
Big Question
"How reliable are our dust devil detections?"
The job is not to find new dust devils. Their job is to understand what a real dust devil looks like in the pressure data.
